<p>We fitted Bayesian negative binomial regression models to the simulation data to estimate the relationship between the number of positive pools or clinical infections and the total number of human infections (
 <italic>I</italic>
 <sub>
  <italic>H</italic>
 </sub>). We used linear models for both the mean parameter (
 <italic>μ</italic>) and the dispersion parameter (
 <italic>ϕ</italic>): 
 <disp-formula id="pntd.0007988.e001">
  <alternatives>
   <graphic xlink:href="pntd.0007988.e001.jpg" id="pntd.0007988.e001g" mimetype="image" position="anchor" orientation="portrait" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
   <math id="M1">
    <msub>
     <mrow>
      <mi>I</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mi>H</mi>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mo>∼</mo>
    <mi mathvariant="normal">NegativeBinomial</mi>
    <mo>(</mo>
    <mrow>
     <mi>μ</mi>
     <mo>,</mo>
     <mi>ϕ</mi>
    </mrow>
    <mo>)</mo>
   </math>
  </alternatives>
 </disp-formula>
 <disp-formula id="pntd.0007988.e002">
  <alternatives>
   <graphic xlink:href="pntd.0007988.e002.jpg" id="pntd.0007988.e002g" mimetype="image" position="anchor" orientation="portrait" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
   <math id="M2">
    <mi>μ</mi>
    <mo>=</mo>
    <msub>
     <mrow>
      <mi>β</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mn>0</mn>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mo>+</mo>
    <msub>
     <mrow>
      <mi>β</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mi>X</mi>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mi>X</mi>
   </math>
  </alternatives>
 </disp-formula>
 <disp-formula id="pntd.0007988.e003">
  <alternatives>
   <graphic xlink:href="pntd.0007988.e003.jpg" id="pntd.0007988.e003g" mimetype="image" position="anchor" orientation="portrait" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
   <math id="M3">
    <mi>ϕ</mi>
    <mo>=</mo>
    <msubsup>
     <mrow>
